    "30094645": {
      "title": "Clinical implications for estimating equations for glomerular filtration rate",
      "abstract": "Chronic kidney disease is a major public health problem, with increasing incidence and prevalence, poor outcomes, and high costs (1, 2). In the United States, the estimated prevalence of all stages of chronic kidney disease is 20 million (1), and the number of patients receiving dialysis should exceed 650000 by 2010 (2). Long-term adverse outcomes associated with chronic kidney disease include kidney failure, complications of impaired kidney function, and, more commonly, an increased risk for cardiovascular disease and death (3). The clinical practice guidelines of the National Kidney Foundation's Kidney Disease Quality Outcome Initiative (NKF-K/DQOI) defined chronic kidney disease as a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) less than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2 or the presence of kidney damage for 3 or more months, regardless of cause (4). The guidelines also provided a system for staging the severity of kidney disease, primarily on the basis of GFR, with stage-specific recommendations for evaluation and management (Table). Table. Classification, Evaluation, and Management of Chronic Kidney Disease The central role of GFR in these guidelines reflects a consensus that it is the best overall measurement of kidney function and the measure most easily understood by physicians and patients. Using GFR, public health campaigns can focus on messages such as Know your number or Save your GFR, a strategy analogous to that used for hypertension or hyperlipidemia. Unlike blood pressure or serum cholesterol levels, however, we cannot measure GFR directly. Urinary clearance is cumbersome to measure in clinical practice and is often inaccurate because of incomplete urine collection. Instead, physicians use the serum creatinine level to estimate GFR. However, in addition to the GFR, the serum creatinine level depends on creatinine generation, extrarenal elimination, and tubular secretion. Using serum creatinine alone to estimate GFR is unsatisfactory and leads to delays in diagnosis and treatment of chronic kidney disease. Estimating equations overcome some of these limitations because they use known demographic and clinical variables as surrogates for the unmeasured physiologic factors that affect serum creatinine level. For this reason, national and international organizations recommend that clinicians use estimating equations for GFR to assess kidney function and that clinical laboratories report estimated GFR whenever someone orders measurement of serum creatinine (4-8). One commonly used estimating equation is that derived from the Modification of Diet in Renal Disease study (MDRD Study equation) (9, 10). When compared to the gold standard of iothalamate clearance, the MDRD Study equation is more accurate than another well-known estimating equation (the CockcroftGault equation), as well as measured urinary creatinine clearance. The MDRD Study equation was the product of a multivariable statistical analysis to estimate GFR in patients with chronic kidney disease (mean GFR, 40 mL/min per 1.73 m2), most of whom were white and had nondiabetic kidney disease. Since then, other studies have reported that the MDRD Study equation accurately estimates GFR in other patients with chronic kidney disease: African Americans with hypertensive nephrosclerosis, patients with diabetic kidney disease, and kidney transplant recipients (11-13). In these studies, measured GFR in approximately 90% of individuals will be within 30% of the estimated GFR. In this issue, Rule and colleagues (14) perform a key test of the MDRD Study equation by measuring its performance across a wide range of GFR. They studied both patients with chronic kidney disease and potential kidney donors (mean GFR [SD], 48 25 and 101 17 mL/min per 1.73 m2, respectively); they also used iothalamate clearance as the gold standard test (14). The MDRD Study equation underestimated GFR by 6.2% in patients with chronic kidney disease and by 29% in the potential kidney donors. In addition, the authors showed that patients with chronic kidney disease had a lower mean measured GFR than kidney donors whose serum creatinine level was in the same range. Finally, with a study sample composed of patients with chronic kidney disease and kidney donor candidates, they developed a new equation to estimate GFR that used age, sex, and a quadratic term for serum creatinine. This paper illustrates an important limitation of current estimating equations based on serum creatininedecreased accuracy in persons with a measured GFR greater than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2and provides important lessons on the use of these equations in clinical practice. There are several possible reasons for decreased accuracy at higher levels of GFR. First, use of serum creatinine in estimating equations requires that the creatinine assay be calibrated to the laboratory that developed the estimating equation. Failure to do so can introduce a systematic bias in the estimated GFR, particularly at a high GFR (15-18). Previous studies of individuals with higher GFR have not carefully considered errors due to calibration (19, 20). Rule and colleagues calibrated the instrument used to measure serum creatinine in their clinical laboratory to the same type of instrument used in the MDRD Study Central Laboratory. However, serum creatinine assays vary across laboratories, even when the same instruments are used (21). In our view, the authors have not convincingly shown that calibration differences do not play a role in the apparent discrepancy between measured and estimated GFR in the kidney donors. Direct calibration by comparison of the results of split samples in the Mayo Clinic and the MDRD Study Central Laboratory would be the definitive method to address this issue. Second, use of regression analysis, by its very nature of best fit to the observed mean, decreases the accuracy of the estimates in populations with different ranges of GFR. Use of an equation developed in patients with decreased GFR would underestimate GFR in individuals with a higher range of GFR, such as a healthy population, and conversely an equation developed in a population with a higher GFR would overestimate GFR in a group with decreased GFR, such as persons with chronic kidney disease. Third, there may be a fundamentally different relationship between serum creatinine and GFR in populations with and without kidney disease. However, in Rule and colleagues' study, the GFR range in patients with chronic kidney disease and those without chronic kidney disease overlaps only slightly; thus, one cannot distinguish between this third possibility and the first two. If indeed there is a different relationship between serum creatinine and GFR, a single equation may not be able to accurately estimate GFR across the entire range of GFR found in health and in disease. Rule and colleagues developed a new equation based on combined data from patients with chronic kidney disease and kidney donors. Proper evaluation of this equation would require testing in an independent population before we can make any statement about its potential for use in clinical practice. Ideally, the population should include many individuals who vary widely with regard to GFR, age, race, ethnicity, body composition, risk factors for chronic kidney disease, and types of chronic kidney disease. The NKF-K/DOQI guidelines for chronic kidney disease and National Kidney Disease Education Program recommendations to report estimated GFR were designed to take into account the uncertainty in the accuracy of GFR estimating equations in the higher range. Persistent reduction in GFR less than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2 is defined as chronic kidney disease; the NKF-K/DOQI guidelines recommend that persons with a GFR less than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2 undergo further evaluation and management (4, 5). Individuals with a GFR greater than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2 and markers of kidney damage, such as proteinuria, also have chronic kidney disease. Individuals with a GFR greater than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2 but without markers of kidney damage do not have chronic kidney disease; a precise estimate of GFR is usually not necessary in these individuals. A specific value of GFR should be reported only if the estimated GFR is less than 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2; higher values should be reported as GFR is 60 mL/min per 1.73 m2. We do not currently have a good understanding of the potential misclassification that may occur in applying these equations in the general population. However, even if an estimating equation has a substantial bias at higher GFRs, such as was reported by Rule and colleagues, the magnitude of the misclassification is probably much less than with the use of serum creatinine alone. It is on the basis of this understanding that large health organizations in the United States, such as the Veterans Health Administration (Patel TG. Personal communication, 2004) and Laboratory Corporation of America (Fleming J. Personal communication, 2003), as well as all clinical laboratories in British Columbia, Canada (Levin A. Personal communication, 2003), and in France (22), have implemented automatic reporting of estimated GFR. These efforts are being coordinated with a campaign to educate physicians, health care organizations, patients, and the public about chronic kidney disease and GFR estimates. What needs to be done to improve these equations? The National Kidney Disease Education Program is leading a national standardization program for serum creatinine, which should minimize limitations related to creatinine assay and calibration. The National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Disease has funded a comprehensive study of individuals with a wide range of GFR and health status to develop improved estimating equations using creatinine and alternative filtration markers, such as cystatin C. New estimating equations should be adopted only after they have been rigorously developed and validated in independent populations. In the"
    },
    "17290561": {
      "title": "Recommendations for improving serum creatinine measurement: a report from the laboratory working group of the National Kidney Disease Education Program",
      "abstract": "BACKGROUND ::: Reliable serum creatinine measurements in glomerular filtration rate (GFR) estimation are critical to ongoing global public health efforts to increase the diagnosis and treatment of chronic kidney disease (CKD). We present an overview of the commonly used methods for the determination of serum creatinine, method limitations, and method performance in conjunction with the development of analytical performance criteria. Available resources for standardization of serum creatinine measurement are discussed, and recommendations for measurement improvement are given. ::: ::: ::: METHODS ::: The National Kidney Disease Education Program (NKDEP) Laboratory Working Group reviewed problems related to serum creatinine measurement for estimating GFR and prepared recommendations to standardize and improve creatinine measurement. ::: ::: ::: RESULTS ::: The NKDEP Laboratory Working Group, in collaboration with international professional organizations, has developed a plan that enables standardization and improved accuracy (trueness) of serum creatinine measurements in clinical laboratories worldwide that includes the use of the estimating equation for GFR based on serum creatinine concentration that was developed from the Modification of Diet in Renal Disease (MDRD) study. ::: ::: ::: CONCLUSIONS ::: The current variability in serum creatinine measurements renders all estimating equations for GFR, including the MDRD Study equation, less accurate in the normal and slightly increased range of serum creatinine concentrations [<133 micromol/L (1.5 mg/dL)], which is the relevant range for detecting CKD [<60 mL.min(-1).(1.73 m2)(-1)]. Many automated routine methods for serum creatinine measurement meet or exceed the required precision; therefore, reduction of analytical bias in creatinine assays is needed. Standardization of calibration does not correct for analytical interferences (nonspecificity bias). The bias and nonspecificity problems associated with some of the routine methods must be addressed."
    },
    "23779490": {
      "title": "Variation in serum creatinine assay calibration: a practical application to glomerular filtration rate estimation",
      "abstract": "Variation in the serum creatinine assay calibration: A practical application to glomerular filtration rate estimation. Background Variation among clinical laboratories in calibration of serum creatinine assays is a source of error in glomerular filtration rate (GFR) estimation equations. We evaluated impact of this variation on GFR estimates. Methods Errors in GFR estimates were computed based on the range of calibration differences from the 1994 College of American Pathologists (CAP) survey using the Modification of Diet in Renal Disease (MDRD) Study GFR equation. Results Mean (95% CI) calibration difference observed in the CAP survey was +0.14 mg/dL (+12.4 μmol/L) [-0.09, +0.37 mg/dL (-7.96, +32.71 μmol/L)]. Errors in GFR estimates using uncalibrated serum creatinine values were lower in individuals with lower estimated GFR. For GFR of 60 mL/min/1.73m 2 , the mean calibration difference in the CAP survey was associated with errors in GFR estimation between -5.5 to -8.1 mL/min/1.73 m 2 (-9.1 to -13.5%) depending on race and sex. The 95% confidence interval for the calibration difference was associated with a maximal range of error in GFR estimates from +4.6 to -18.1 mL/min/1.73 m 2 (+7.6 to -30.2%). Errors of this magnitude at an estimated GFR of 60 mL/min/1.73 m 2 are not likely to be of clinical significance. However, errors at higher levels of estimated GFR would be greater, making GFR estimates in this range unreliable. Conclusion Recalibration of serum creatinine assays to the MDRD Study clinical laboratory would improve accuracy of GFR estimation using the MDRD Study equation, but is not practical for all clinical laboratories. As an interim solution, clinical laboratories could report GFR estimates 2 without recalibration with an acceptable accuracy."
    }
  },
  "generator": "fallback_v4"
}